flashcards.description:
• DNA polymerase I functions as exonuclease from 5’ to 3’. It separated RNA primer from DNA and fills the gap with the nucleotides from 5’ to 3’.
  • These fragments are later joined by the enzyme DNA ligase.
flashcards.title: Termination of DNA replication
flashcards.summary: The RNA primer from the Okazaki fragments and from the leading daughter strand are removed and a continuous DNA strand is produced by the action of DNA polymerase I and DNA ligase.

flashcards.description:
• In eukaryotes the process of DNA replication takes place at the S phase of the cell cycle.
  • In prokaryotes it occurs during binary fission.
  • DNA replication and cell division cycle should be highly coordinated. 
  • A failure of cell division after DNA replication results in polyploidy.
flashcards.title: Introduction to Replication Mechanism
flashcards.summary: • The process of duplication of a single DNA molecule into two daughter DNA molecules is called autocatalysis or replication.

flashcards.description:
Origin of Replication

  • The origin of replication on the E. coli chromosome is a specific sequence called ori C.
  • Replication proceed on both sides from ori. Therefore, called bidirectional replication.

Unwinding of DNA helix

  • Enzyme helicases unwind the DNA helix  by ATP hydrolysis and unzips the two strands.
  • Unzipping forms a Y shaped configuration called as replication fork.
     
  • Single strand binding protein (SSBPs) bind to ss DNA and prevent recoiling of the two strands.

Formation of RNA primer

  • After separation of the two strands, each strand act as template for DNA replication. 
  • The DNA dependent DNA polymerase cannot initiate the process of replication on their own. 
  • Therefore, there is a requirement of an RNA polymerase or primase.
  • Primase synthesises a complementing primer RNA. (The strand that provides the necessary 3’ OH terminus is called a primer.
  • The synthesis is in the 5’→ 3’ direction.
flashcards.title: Initiation of Replication
flashcards.summary: DNA replication begins at particular nucleotide sequences on DNA called origin of replication. Prokaryotes have a single origin of replication and eukaryotes have many. After separation of the two strands by helicase enzyme, each strand act as template for DNA replication. There is the requirement for synthesis of short RNA primer to initiate the process of replication.

flashcards.description:
The formation of new chains is catalyzed by an enzyme DNA polymerase.
In prokaryotes DNA polymerases are of three types.

  • DNA polymerase III are highly efficient enzymes as they have to catalyse polymerisation of a large number of nucleotides in a very short time. 
  • E. coli that has only 4.6 ×106 bp completes the process of replication within 18 minutes. Therefore, average rate of polymerisation has to be approximately 2000 bp per second. 
  • Polymerases have to be fast, and they also have to catalyse the reaction with high degree of accuracy. Any mistake during replication would result into mutations.

Activation of nucleotides

  • Replication is energetically expensive process.
  • Deoxyribonucleotide diphosphates or deoxyribonucleoside triphosphate serve dual purpose.
    • Acts as substrate for polymerization.
    • Also provide energy for the replication.

Elongation

DNA dependent DNA polymerase adds complementary deoxyribonucleotides towards the 3’ end of the primer. This leads to elongation of the strand in 5’→ 3’ direction.

  • DNA polymerase catalyses polymerization only in direction 5’→3’ direction.
  • In the template strand with polarity 3’→5’ , the replication is continuous, and the new strand is called leading strand.
  • In the template strand with polarity 5’→3’ , the replication is discontinuous, and the new strand is called lagging strand.
  • These fragments of lagging strand made in semi-discontinuous replications are called Okazaki fragments (1,000 to 2,000 bases) after their discoverers Reiji and Tuneko Okazaki. 
  • The problem is solved by synthesizing the new strand on the 5′ to 3′ template in a series of short fragments, each synthesized in the “backward” direction; that is, with the customary 5′–3′ polarity.
  • Okazaki fragments are found in replicating DNA of both prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
  • Thus, the lagging strand is synthesized discontinuously, and the leading strand is synthesized continuously. This is called semi-discontinuous replication.
flashcards.title: Elongation of DNA during Replication
flashcards.summary: DNA dependent DNA polymerase III adds complementary deoxyribonucleotides towards the 3’ end of the primer. This leads to elongation of the strand in 5’→ 3’ direction.

question.question_text: Discontinuously synthesized strands of DNA adjacent to ____A____ DNA template are joined together by ____B____.

solution.data: The template with polarity 5'→3', it is discontinuous. The discontinuously synthesised fragments are later joined by the enzyme DNA ligase.

question.question_text: DNA replication occurs just prior to the fission in

solution.data: Bacterial cells show DNA replication just prior to the fission.

question.question_text: During which phase of the cell cycle does replication of DNA takes place in eukaryotes?

solution.data: In eukaryotes, the replication of DNA takes place at S-phase of the cell-cycle.

question.question_text: During DNA replication, Okazaki fragments are used to elongate
answer_options: The leading strand away from replication fork
The lagging strand away from the replication fork

solution.data: The polymerase molecules responsible for construction of the two new strands of DNA both move in 3’ → 5’ direction along the template, and both construct a chain that grows from 5’→3’ and consequently one of the newly synthesized strands grow towards fork (leading strand) and the other strand grows away from the fork (lagging strand). Therefore, Okazaki fragments are used to elongate lagging strand away from the replication fork.
